snippet.textDisplay:
If you haven't heard the story of this commercial, you should, It's amazing! Bill Murray, who has never done a commercial before, committed to do this one for a good friend of his two weeks before the Super Bowl! Most commercials for this event are wrapped up at least two months before the air date. During this time, the ad agency had to secure the rights to use both the movie (from Sony Pictures, which owns the rights now) and "I've Got You, Babe" (from Warner Music Group.)


I originally thought that they digitally composited Bill into scenes from the movie but they actually shot the commercial in the same town in which Groundhog Day was filmed, using the same people and locations. To remain faithful to the spirit of the original movie, the cast and crew even stayed in the same motel tha the original cast and crew stayed in during the original filming. It's amazing to think they recreated the look of the original film some 27 years later.


What a clever, faithful, but thoroughly updated ("Emotional Support" beaver vest, restraint vest when riding in the Jeep) homage to a truly wonderful film. I haven't seen all of the Super Bowl Commercials but this one was may favorite of all I've seen and it's only grown in stature sine I've learned its backstory.
